1 Justification a.k.a. The Huddled Masses 2.0: Give Me Your Poor No More?

With the recent decision to temporarily suspend new immigrant visas, immigration is again on a lot of people’s minds. While nonimmigrant visas, including work authorizations like the much sought-after H-1B type visas, pertain to another visa category, the clampdown - however provisional - on immigrant visas, together with the entire COVID-19 situation, has made the already uneasy hiring process more uncertain and tumultuous for everybody involved, from employers to H-1B seekers. Luckily, uncertainty is statisticians’ daily bread. Questions to do with stochasticity, optimization, and Bayesian statistics come to the fore. Under these strenuous circumstances, how might we best plug foreigners in the U.S. job market, such that parameters like the approval rate on the one hand, or wage-yields of fresh graduates on the other, are optimized? Here at Columbia, we have long been in the vanguard of developing solutions to deal with these kinds of pressing industry questions with the help of Stan. Using Stan, this project aims at getting to the bottom of these and other questions, with the help of posterior distributions, while taking into account the latest data in the field.

1.1 Data

The U.S. Labor Department’s Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OLFC) uses a designated website that serves as the repository of the latest labor statistics pertaining to immigration/work visa and the like, with datasets parsed by Fiscal Year (e.g. the Federal government’s FY 2019 went from October 1, 2018, through September 30, 2019), and including roughly 34 variables such as, inter alia, Foreign Workers’ Country of Origin, Country of Birth, Wage, Class of Admission, their university Major, the name of the University itself, Size of the Employer, NAICS code of the job, and many, many others. Honing in on one kind of visa in particular, the covetted H-1Bs, let’s look into the latest complete dataset, which is FY 2019.

Some cleaning and subset…

d.sub <- subset(d, select = c("emp_name", "emp_city", "emp_size", "wage", "job_city", # Subsetting for H-1Bs and leaving behind what's extraneous.
                              "job_state", "job_edu", "job_major", "fw_coc", "fw_cob", # fw_coc Foreign Worker - Country of Citizenship, fw_cob Foreign Worker - Country of Birth
                              "fw_class_of_admission", "fw_edu", "fw_major", "fw_edu_yrs", "fw_edu_name",
                              "naics_code", "naics_title"),
                fw_class_of_admission == "H-1B")
